\begin_layout Section
Unique Factorization
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
prime number
\end_layout

\begin_layout Definition
an integer 
\begin_inset Formula $p\geq2$
\end_inset

 s.t.
 given a factorization 
\begin_inset Formula $p=mn$
\end_inset

 with positive integers 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $m=1$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $n=1$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Lemma
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 be a prime number, and 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

 non-zero integers s.t.
 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $mn$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $p|m$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $p|n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 does not divide one of 
\begin_inset Formula $m,n$
\end_inset

, say 
\begin_inset Formula $m$
\end_inset

.
 Then the GCD of 
\begin_inset Formula $p,m$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 By 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "thm:3"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

, there exists 
\begin_inset Formula $a,b$
\end_inset

 s.t.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
1=ap+bm.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n=nap+bmn
\]

\end_inset

Since 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 divides 
\begin_inset Formula $mn$
\end_inset

, i.e.
 for some integer 
\begin_inset Formula $c$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $mn=pc$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n=\left(na+bc\right)p,
\]

\end_inset

p divides 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Every positive integer 
\begin_inset Formula $n\geq2$
\end_inset

 can be expressed as a product of prime numbers (not necessarily distinct),
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n=p_{1}\cdots p_{r},
\]

\end_inset

uniquely determined up to the order of the factors.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
It is easy to prove the existence of such prime factorization by well ordering.
 About the uniqueness, refer to Chap.7 of A Friendly Introduction to Number
 Theory by Joseph H.
 Silverman.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Separator plain
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
More concisely, we can write the prime factorization into 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
n=p_{1}^{m_{1}}p_{2}^{m_{2}}\cdots p_{r}^{m_{r}}
\]

\end_inset

for some nonnegative integers 
\begin_inset Formula $m_{1},m_{2},\dots,m_{r}$
\end_inset

.
 By writing a rational number 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 in its lowest terms and factorizing the numerator and denominator, we obtain
 a factorization of 
\begin_inset Formula $a$
\end_inset

 itself.
\end_layout

